@bolkedebruin Thank you for the pointers, I was referring to the flask request context. Added the tests and adjusted the commented out part in the function below it. PTAL

CI failure seems to be unrelated. I can kick off another try if you prefer( observed flakiness in CI, don't want to consume too much travis resources just to retry on flaky tests).

CC @Fokko

@feng-tao  @yrqls21  Sorry I was wrong. It looks like gunicorn and FAB aren't cohabiting very well.

I cleared the db in my local airflow with RBAC enabled. When rerunning `airflow webserver`, it is now throwing many IntegrityError while trying to instantiate the appbuilder (FAB eagerly populates missing rows in its rbac-related tables when it is instantiated). My suspicion is that when we had the extra app creation line, app and appbuilder were created once and cached, so when gunicorn spun up each worker it just used the cached object; now that we removed the line, each worker attempts to populate the same set of rows and it's causing a race condition (which resulted in bad rows generated in `ab_permission_view` and `ab_permission_view_role`). 

Let me know if you can replicate this issue.I think the right thing to do is to revert the change, fix the race condition if possible, and then come back to address the double app creation issue.

@jgao54 I think we should definitely revert this PR.

Since gunicorn spins up actual unix process, the app and appbuilder objects won't be shared. But I agree with your theory that FAB won't work well when starting two apps at the same time( set gunicorn worker # to 1 would stop the error). The least we can do is to limit the change to only legacy UI. I'll allocate sometime next week or later to dive into the race condition issue.

Apologize for missing the RBAC with fresh db test part and thank you for spotting it.

@Fokko The hive part looks good to me. 

@yrqls21 I don't understand the reference to `airflow_travis.cfg`. Do you mean that in `default_airflow.cfg` you had to use `{{` while in `airflow_travis.cfg` only `{` would work?

The Jira issue is a bit confusing though. The proposal is to put `host` at the end, but AFAICS that didn't change. Or am I overlooking something?
